84
00:08:33.597 --> 00:08:35.766
(SOMBER MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

85
00:09:12.052 --> 00:09:13.217
(MUSIC FADES)

86
00:09:13.219 --> 00:09:14.680
WOMAN: They sing lies.

87
00:09:16.056 --> 00:09:17.808
These foolish common folk.

88
00:09:19.434 --> 00:09:22.187
Lies of his heroism
and goodness.

89
00:09:24.230 --> 00:09:25.774
But blood debts are owed.

90
00:09:27.483 --> 00:09:30.195
And generations
of his victims hunt him.

91
00:09:32.155 --> 00:09:33.364
For in truth...

92
00:09:35.033 --> 00:09:37.701
none were more wicked
and wanton

93
00:09:37.703 --> 00:09:40.371
than the murderous bandit
Robin Hood...

94
00:09:42.165 --> 00:09:43.792
and his Little John.

95
00:09:48.171 --> 00:09:49.422
ROBIN: Speak to Thomas.

96
00:09:51.049 --> 00:09:53.633
He were hanged in the South.

97
00:09:53.635 --> 00:09:54.595
ROBIN: Will?

98
00:09:56.137 --> 00:09:57.556
They gutted him.

99
00:09:59.265 --> 00:10:00.892
I have no one else to ask.

100
00:10:03.186 --> 00:10:04.437
What happened?

101
00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:08.399
(SIGHS) My name is Edward.

102
00:10:09.234 --> 00:10:10.694
ROBIN: Who was Edward?

103
00:10:12.278 --> 00:10:15.572
I met him on the road.
ten summers ago.

104
00:10:15.574 --> 00:10:18.199
His brother died.
And he were going to grow

105
00:10:18.201 --> 00:10:20.245
rye and peas
on his brother's land.

106
00:10:22.288 --> 00:10:23.999
No one knew Edward's face.

107
00:10:25.709 --> 00:10:26.835
So I killed him.

108
00:10:28.128 --> 00:10:29.462
Now I am Edward.

109
00:10:30.964 --> 00:10:32.508
And Margaret's a good wife.

110
00:10:33.383 --> 00:10:34.635
It's a good farm.

111
00:10:35.719 --> 00:10:36.887
What happened?

112
00:10:38.346 --> 00:10:40.265
A family on the land
found me out.

113
00:10:41.099 --> 00:10:44.308
Took my farm.
Took my Margaret.

114
00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:45.771
Tried to take my life.

115
00:10:49.315 --> 00:10:51.315
I cannot take back alone
what is mine.

116
00:10:51.317 --> 00:10:52.653
It's not yours.

117
00:10:54.655 --> 00:10:55.947
EDWARD: It's my family.

118
00:11:01.202 --> 00:11:02.538
I'm tired. John.

119
00:11:04.122 --> 00:11:05.541
Edward.

120
00:11:07.959 --> 00:11:09.335
I'm tired. Edward.

121
00:11:13.507 --> 00:11:17.343
(SIGHS) It would be
a mighty battle.

122
00:11:17.969 --> 00:11:19.387
One for the stories.

123
00:11:25.519 --> 00:11:27.060
They are strong?

124
00:11:27.062 --> 00:11:28.063
Aye.

125
00:11:29.230 --> 00:11:31.397
They come from an old family.

126
00:11:31.399 --> 00:11:32.901
They say from Viking blood.

127
00:11:34.736 --> 00:11:37.070
There's a story
that once their elderfather

128
00:11:37.072 --> 00:11:38.073
fought a bear.

129
00:11:39.866 --> 00:11:42.452
It would be
a mighty battle. Robin.

130
00:11:45.413 --> 00:11:46.665
How many are there?

131
00:11:48.041 --> 00:11:50.001
EDWARD: Four? Five?

132
00:11:50.502 --> 00:11:52.087
Together we can best them.

133
00:11:55.549 --> 00:11:56.925
We'll likely die.

134
00:12:03.557 --> 00:12:09.102
TRAVELER:
♪ As I was walking all alone ♪

135
00:12:09.104 --> 00:12:14.398
♪ I heard two crows
a-making a moan ♪

136
00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:20.196
♪ One said to the other.
did say-o ♪

137
00:12:20.198 --> 00:12:24.701
♪ "Where shall we go
and dine today-o? ♪

138
00:12:24.703 --> 00:12:30.456
♪ "Where shall we go
and dine today?" ♪

139
00:12:30.458 --> 00:12:34.878
♪ In behind
that old turf wall ♪

140
00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:40.133
♪ I sense there lies
a new slain knight ♪

141
00:12:40.135 --> 00:12:45.847
♪ And nobody knows
that he lies there-o ♪

142
00:12:45.849 --> 00:12:50.309
♪ But his hawk. and his hound
and his lady fair-o ♪

143
00:12:50.311 --> 00:12:54.733
♪ His hawk. and his hound
and his lady fair ♪

144
00:13:02.448 --> 00:13:07.952
♪ Many a one for him
shall moan ♪

145
00:13:07.954 --> 00:13:13.166
♪ None shall know
where he has gone ♪

146
00:13:13.168 --> 00:13:19.881
♪ O'er his white bones.
when they are bare-o ♪

147
00:13:19.883 --> 00:13:24.928
♪ Wind shall blow
for evermore-o ♪

148
00:13:24.930 --> 00:13:29.893
♪ Wind shall blow
for evermore ♪

149
00:13:31.645 --> 00:13:32.813
Robin!

150
00:13:34.606 --> 00:13:35.857
Robin!

151
00:13:37.483 --> 00:13:39.820
Bread? (LAUGHS)

152
00:13:41.655 --> 00:13:43.073
This is a good adventure.

153
00:13:45.158 --> 00:13:46.201
A good adventure.

154
00:13:49.705 --> 00:13:52.747
You remember
when we met the potter.

155
00:13:52.749 --> 00:13:55.834
did we leave him naked
or did we kill him?

156
00:13:55.836 --> 00:13:57.711
Oh. I tried to tell the story

157
00:13:57.713 --> 00:13:59.840
and someone said
we left him naked.

158
00:14:00.298 --> 00:14:01.675
But I couldn't remember.

159
00:14:02.593 --> 00:14:04.469
You always told
it well. Robin.

160
00:14:06.555 --> 00:14:08.139
Why would we leave him naked?

161
00:14:09.683 --> 00:14:10.892
I don't know.

162
00:14:12.769 --> 00:14:14.187
It were a jest.

163
00:14:15.522 --> 00:14:16.815
We never met a potter.

164
00:14:17.733 --> 00:14:19.691
What do you mean
we never met him?

165
00:14:19.693 --> 00:14:20.900
ROBIN: I mean.
that never happened.

166
00:14:20.902 --> 00:14:23.029
It's just a story
you heard somewhere.

167
00:14:24.405 --> 00:14:25.572
(SCOFFS)

168
00:14:25.574 --> 00:14:26.950
ROBIN: But if we did meet
a potter.

169
00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:29.534
we killed him.

170
00:14:29.536 --> 00:14:31.452
I'd remember
if it were a story.

171
00:14:31.454 --> 00:14:33.414
(GRUNTS) Here!

172
00:14:33.874 --> 00:14:35.291
Tell me about your wife.

173
00:14:38.211 --> 00:14:39.295
Margaret.

174
00:14:41.381 --> 00:14:43.214
She's a good woman.

175
00:14:43.216 --> 00:14:46.968
She's a very good woman.
She's pious.

176
00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:48.887
She teaches me prayerfulness.

177
00:14:48.889 --> 00:14:50.140
Paint a portrait.

178
00:14:51.975 --> 00:14:53.268
Paint a portrait?

179
00:14:54.728 --> 00:14:57.313
(CHUCKLES) Paint a portrait?

180
00:15:01.818 --> 00:15:06.364
She has hair that's red.

181
00:15:07.032 --> 00:15:08.657
ROBIN: Red like?

182
00:15:08.659 --> 00:15:10.867
Red like fresh blood.

183
00:15:10.869 --> 00:15:13.036
ROBIN: No. not blood.
No. no. no.

184
00:15:13.038 --> 00:15:15.874
Something that's red
and that's good. like her.

185
00:15:16.958 --> 00:15:18.585
Red like... I don't know.

186
00:15:22.673 --> 00:15:24.130
Like the setting sun.

187
00:15:24.132 --> 00:15:27.844
Aye. like
the setting summer sun.

188
00:15:29.220 --> 00:15:31.680
Margaret's a good wife.

189
00:15:31.682 --> 00:15:34.851
With hair that's red
like the setting summer sun.

190
00:15:36.728 --> 00:15:38.021
She cares for me.

191
00:15:39.523 --> 00:15:40.566
And I care for her.

192
00:15:43.484 --> 00:15:45.070
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

193
00:15:45.696 --> 00:15:46.655
ROBIN: Hmm.

194
00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:53.036
EDWARD: Robin. there are open
lands past the mountains.

195
00:15:55.205 --> 00:15:56.998
Many places to begin again.

196
00:16:02.003 --> 00:16:04.047
No. I do not aim
to begin again.

197
00:16:09.553 --> 00:16:11.179
I aim for a right death.

198
00:16:13.682 --> 00:16:15.807
(DOG BARKING)

199
00:16:15.809 --> 00:16:18.061
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

200
00:16:37.122 --> 00:16:39.750
(WIND BLOWING)

201
00:16:59.102 --> 00:17:01.312
(TENSE MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

202
00:17:09.696 --> 00:17:11.782
-(MAN YELLS. GROANS)
-(KNIFE SLASHING)

203
00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:16.662
(GAGGING AND GASPING)

204
00:17:35.305 --> 00:17:37.473
(TENSE MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

205
00:17:52.656 --> 00:17:54.030
-(EDWARD GRUNTS)
-MARGARET: Edward!

206
00:17:54.032 --> 00:17:55.156
HENDRIE'S FATHER:
Go. Hendrie!

207
00:17:55.158 --> 00:17:56.908
MARGARET: Edward!

208
00:17:56.910 --> 00:17:59.287
Go. Hendrie. run! Now!

209
00:17:59.788 --> 00:18:01.538
-Edward!
-Back!

210
00:18:01.540 --> 00:18:03.584
-(HENDRIE PANTING)
-Hendrie. get the others!

211
00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:05.544
MARGARET: Edward!

212
00:18:06.503 --> 00:18:09.172
(PANTING) Edward. my love...

213
00:18:10.549 --> 00:18:12.423
Watch over Little Margaret.

214
00:18:12.425 --> 00:18:13.925
-(MAN YELLS)
-(MARGARET SCREAMS)

215
00:18:13.927 --> 00:18:15.971
(SCREAMING)

216
00:18:17.347 --> 00:18:19.390
(EDWARD AND MAN GRUNTING)

217
00:18:24.437 --> 00:18:26.607
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

218
00:18:27.858 --> 00:18:29.400
(PANTING)

219
00:18:30.902 --> 00:18:32.278
(CRYING)

220
00:18:35.532 --> 00:18:36.533
(GRUNTS)

221
00:18:50.171 --> 00:18:52.382
(MUFFLED POUNDING)

222
00:18:56.427 --> 00:18:57.888
(EDWARD GRUNTING)

223
00:19:03.184 --> 00:19:05.687
(YELLING MANIACALLY)

224
00:19:06.563 --> 00:19:08.398
(BREATHING RAGGEDLY)

225
00:19:12.569 --> 00:19:14.320
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

226
00:19:22.078 --> 00:19:24.080
(EDWARD CRYING SOFTLY)

227
00:19:34.340 --> 00:19:35.884
(SNIFFLES AND GURGLES)

228
00:19:39.137 --> 00:19:40.972
(SOBBING)

229
00:19:49.314 --> 00:19:51.775
(EDWARD SCREAMS)

230
00:19:54.235 --> 00:19:56.446
(CONTINUES SOBBING)

231
00:19:57.238 --> 00:19:58.740
(LITTLE MARGARET WHIMPERS)

232
00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:10.542
Little one. don't worry.

233
00:20:10.544 --> 00:20:14.253
Don't worry.
Come here. come here.

234
00:20:14.255 --> 00:20:16.883
You're safe.
You're safe. daughter.

235
00:20:20.804 --> 00:20:23.056
Let us pray. Let us pray.

236
00:20:25.308 --> 00:20:28.309
O Lord. our God.

237
00:20:28.311 --> 00:20:32.148
grant us grace to desire Thee
with our whole heart.

238
00:20:32.733 --> 00:20:34.816
Come on now. pray.

239
00:20:34.818 --> 00:20:37.986
BOTH: And in finding Thee.
we may love Thee.

240
00:20:37.988 --> 00:20:40.947
And in loving Thee.
we may hate those sins

241
00:20:40.949 --> 00:20:43.658
from which Thou hast
redeemed us.

242
00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:46.705
For the sake of Jesus Christ.
Amen.

243
00:20:48.665 --> 00:20:51.750
Yes. Yes. good.

244
00:20:51.752 --> 00:20:54.671
Good. (SOBS. GRUNTS)

245
00:21:06.349 --> 00:21:07.601
(SHEEP BLEATING)

246
00:21:56.316 --> 00:21:57.317
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

247
00:22:00.779 --> 00:22:01.988
HENDRIE: (WHISPERING)
I'm sorry.

248
00:22:04.032 --> 00:22:05.075
I'm sorry.

249
00:22:08.119 --> 00:22:09.204
I'm sorry.

250
00:22:10.747 --> 00:22:12.999
It were that when I woke.

251
00:22:15.376 --> 00:22:17.003
It were that when I woke.

252
00:22:18.254 --> 00:22:19.838
SHEPHERD: Cousin.

253
00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:21.842
It were that when I woke.

254
00:22:23.343 --> 00:22:24.761
I'm sorry.

255
00:22:26.137 --> 00:22:31.265
TRAVELER: ♪ The wind
between the north and east ♪

256
00:22:31.267 --> 00:22:34.855
♪ Blowed every chill
and cold ♪

257
00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:41.275
♪ Or coldly blowed to me.
at least ♪

258
00:22:41.277 --> 00:22:44.740
♪ My clothes were thin
and old ♪

259
00:22:45.782 --> 00:22:50.493
♪ The grass all dropping wet
with dew ♪

260
00:22:50.495 --> 00:22:53.248
♪ Low bent their tiny spears ♪

261
00:22:54.666 --> 00:22:58.837
♪ The lowly daisy bended too ♪

262
00:22:59.671 --> 00:23:04.425
♪ More lowly with my tears ♪

263
00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:11.808
♪ Oh. luckless youth
to sorrow born ♪

264
00:23:12.518 --> 00:23:15.228
♪ Shun'd son of poverty ♪

265
00:23:16.855 --> 00:23:21.442
♪ The world made gamely
sport and scorn ♪

266
00:23:22.152 --> 00:23:24.487
♪ And grinning infamy ♪

267
00:23:25.989 --> 00:23:30.074
♪ Unequalled though
my sorrow seems ♪

268
00:23:30.076 --> 00:23:33.537
♪ But great indeed they are ♪

269
00:23:33.539 --> 00:23:37.417
♪ Oh hear my sorrows
for my stream ♪

270
00:23:38.710 --> 00:23:42.923
♪ You'll find an equal there ♪

271
00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:47.969
♪ The land and Eddings
are no more ♪

272
00:23:49.054 --> 00:23:52.015
♪ The pastures too are gone ♪

273
00:23:53.850 --> 00:23:58.687
♪ The greens. the meadows
and the moors ♪

274
00:23:58.689 --> 00:24:01.397
♪ Are all cut up and gone ♪

275
00:24:01.399 --> 00:24:03.652
ELDERFATHER: We cry
to Thee. O Lord.

276
00:24:05.278 --> 00:24:07.906
Do Thou have mercy upon us?

277
00:24:09.199 --> 00:24:11.199
FAMILY:
And grant forgiveness.

278
00:24:11.201 --> 00:24:15.328
ELDERFATHER: O King of heaven.
and everlasting Lord.

279
00:24:15.330 --> 00:24:19.375
receive our prayers
which we pour forth.

280
00:24:20.836 --> 00:24:22.669
FAMILY:
And grant forgiveness.

281
00:24:22.671 --> 00:24:27.340
ELDERFATHER: Visit the sick.
bring forth the captive.

282
00:24:27.342 --> 00:24:30.929
help the widow and the orphan.

283
00:24:32.263 --> 00:24:34.806
FAMILY:
And grant forgiveness.

284
00:24:34.808 --> 00:24:39.936
ELDERFATHER: We have sinned
and departed from Thee.

285
00:24:39.938 --> 00:24:45.235
Wilt Thou. the Redeemer
of all. save us?

286
00:24:46.277 --> 00:24:48.277
FAMILY:
And grant forgiveness.

287
00:24:48.279 --> 00:24:51.197
Have mercy on the penitent

288
00:24:51.199 --> 00:24:55.370
and wash away
the stains of sin.

289
00:24:57.038 --> 00:24:59.165
FAMILY:
And grant forgiveness.

290
00:25:00.834 --> 00:25:02.586
ALL: Amen.

291
00:25:07.924 --> 00:25:10.008
(EERIE MUSIC PLAYING)

292
00:25:10.010 --> 00:25:12.178
(MUFFLED FIRE CRACKLING)

293
00:25:17.684 --> 00:25:19.394
(DISTANT THUD)

294
00:25:26.777 --> 00:25:28.779
(DISTANT MAN SHOUTS)

295
00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:31.698
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

296
00:25:34.993 --> 00:25:37.162
(FLAMES WHOOSHING)

297
00:25:48.089 --> 00:25:49.591
MAN 1: Kill him!

298
00:25:50.216 --> 00:25:52.177
(MAN 2 YELLS)

299
00:25:56.765 --> 00:25:58.099
MAN: Godwyn!

300
00:26:00.101 --> 00:26:02.270
-(GRUNTING)
-(ROBIN YELLS)

301
00:26:04.105 --> 00:26:06.650
(ROBIN COUGHING)

302
00:26:07.483 --> 00:26:08.443
(SCREAMS)

303
00:26:10.946 --> 00:26:12.573
(SCREAMING)

304
00:26:14.658 --> 00:26:15.826
(PANTING)

305
00:26:17.035 --> 00:26:19.410
(SCREAMS)

306
00:26:19.412 --> 00:26:21.832
(ROBIN GRUNTS. COUGHS)

307
00:26:22.916 --> 00:26:25.501
-(ROBIN GRUNTS)
-(MAN SCREAMING)

308
00:26:27.337 --> 00:26:29.255
(MAN WHIMPERING LOUDLY)

309
00:26:34.135 --> 00:26:35.635
MAN: No!

310
00:26:35.637 --> 00:26:36.805
(MAN SCREAMS)

311
00:26:38.056 --> 00:26:39.975
(GROANS)

312
00:26:41.351 --> 00:26:42.853
(ROBIN COUGHS)

313
00:26:44.354 --> 00:26:45.856
(MAN GRUNTING)

314
00:26:46.690 --> 00:26:47.941
(BOTH YELLING)

315
00:26:49.776 --> 00:26:51.361
(MAN SCREAMING)

316
00:26:57.909 --> 00:26:59.367
(ROBIN PANTING)

317
00:26:59.369 --> 00:27:01.580
(MAN GROANING)

318
00:27:06.877 --> 00:27:08.920
-(CONTINUES PANTING)
-(MAN GRUNTING IN PANIC)

319
00:27:15.886 --> 00:27:17.387
(BOTH SCREAM)

320
00:27:21.016 --> 00:27:22.851
(ROBIN GASPS. GROANS)

321
00:27:24.352 --> 00:27:25.604
(ROBIN GRUNTS)

322
00:27:27.105 --> 00:27:29.608
(MAN SCREAMING)

323
00:27:32.027 --> 00:27:33.612
(YELLS)

324
00:27:34.863 --> 00:27:36.865
(MAN WHEEZING LOUDLY)

325
00:27:54.299 --> 00:27:55.676
(ROBIN COUGHS)

326
00:27:58.595 --> 00:28:00.764
(MAN GRUNTING WEAKLY)

327
00:28:02.516 --> 00:28:05.308
No. Please. Please.

328
00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:08.394
(CRYING) Please. please!
(SCREAMING)

329
00:28:08.396 --> 00:28:11.399
-(ROBIN YELLS. GRUNTS)
-(FLESH SQUELCHES)

330
00:28:11.858 --> 00:28:13.068
(ROBIN COUGHING)

331
00:28:20.325 --> 00:28:22.410
-(EDWARD SCREAMS)
-(POUNDING ON DOOR)

332
00:28:29.125 --> 00:28:30.085
(EDWARD SCREAMS)

333
00:28:32.045 --> 00:28:35.048
(EDWARD AND
LITTLE MARGARET COUGHING)

334
00:28:38.552 --> 00:28:41.469
-EDWARD: Margaret? Margaret!
-ROBIN: No. no.

335
00:28:41.471 --> 00:28:43.429
No! (BREATHING HEAVILY)

336
00:28:43.431 --> 00:28:44.766
(LITTLE MARGARET COUGHS)

337
00:28:45.684 --> 00:28:48.019
ROBIN: John! Don't!

338
00:28:53.316 --> 00:28:55.652
ELDERFATHER: Little John!

339
00:29:02.701 --> 00:29:07.203
Twenty winters ago.
you murdered my cousin.

340
00:29:07.205 --> 00:29:09.124
Walter of Hathersage.

341
00:29:10.542 --> 00:29:13.417
You have murdered my sons

342
00:29:13.419 --> 00:29:15.046
and my grandson.

343
00:29:16.089 --> 00:29:17.340
As wergild...

344
00:29:17.799 --> 00:29:20.800
I accept your life...

345
00:29:20.802 --> 00:29:23.803
and the life of your daughter.

346
00:29:23.805 --> 00:29:25.098
(ROBIN GRUNTS ANGRILY)

347
00:29:28.769 --> 00:29:31.104
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

348
00:29:32.272 --> 00:29:33.273
(GRUNTS ANGRILY)

349
00:29:38.028 --> 00:29:38.987
(ROBIN GRUNTING)

350
00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:41.239
(ROBIN GROANS)

351
00:30:02.343 --> 00:30:03.386
(MACE SWOOSHING)

352
00:30:05.471 --> 00:30:07.057
(BOTH GRUNTING)

353
00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:09.810
(ROBIN GROANS)

354
00:30:13.146 --> 00:30:14.314
(ROBIN GRUNTING)

355
00:30:17.818 --> 00:30:19.152
(ELDERFATHER GRUNTS)

356
00:30:22.155 --> 00:30:24.240
-(ROBIN GRUNTING)
-(ELDERFATHER GROANING)

357
00:30:25.659 --> 00:30:26.868
(ROBIN GROANS)

358
00:30:32.457 --> 00:30:33.416
(ROBIN GRUNTS)

359
00:30:37.003 --> 00:30:38.213
-(HELMET CLANGS)
-(ROBIN GRUNTS)

360
00:30:39.548 --> 00:30:40.924
(GROANS)

361
00:30:42.593 --> 00:30:45.470
-(ELDERFATHER YELLS)
-(ROBIN SCREAMING)

362
00:30:48.807 --> 00:30:50.851
(GASPING)

363
00:31:01.945 --> 00:31:04.280
-(ELDERFATHER GRUNTS)
-(SCREAMS)

364
00:31:08.284 --> 00:31:11.121
(ROBIN GROANS.
GURGLES AND COUGHS)

365
00:31:15.333 --> 00:31:16.292
(GAGS)

366
00:31:23.967 --> 00:31:26.052
(VOICES WHISPERING
INDISTINCTLY)

367
00:31:31.725 --> 00:31:33.268
MAN: (WHISPERING)
...heinous crimes...

368
00:31:35.353 --> 00:31:38.982
...slayer of man.
woman and child...

369
00:31:41.484 --> 00:31:42.485
(BLOW LANDS)

370
00:31:46.406 --> 00:31:48.033
No...

371
00:31:53.539 --> 00:31:55.246
No...

372
00:31:55.248 --> 00:31:59.584
(ECHOING) No! No!
No! No! No!

373
00:31:59.586 --> 00:32:01.421
(YELLING) No!

374
00:32:02.422 --> 00:32:04.215
No!

375
00:32:06.467 --> 00:32:08.845
(CART RATTLING)

376
00:32:11.139 --> 00:32:13.349
(ROBIN BREATHING WEAKLY)

377
00:32:39.793 --> 00:32:42.003
(WIND BLOWING)

378
00:32:52.598 --> 00:32:54.558
(KNIFE SIZZLING)

379
00:32:57.769 --> 00:32:59.143
(FLESH SIZZLING)

380
00:32:59.145 --> 00:33:00.689
(ROBIN SCREAMING)

381
00:33:09.531 --> 00:33:10.446
(ROBIN GROANS)

382
00:33:10.448 --> 00:33:12.534
(INDISTINCT VOICES
CONTINUE WHISPERING)

383
00:33:14.703 --> 00:33:15.996
EDWARD: Robin?

384
00:33:16.955 --> 00:33:20.291
I've heard stories
of a Priory hidden away.

385
00:33:21.877 --> 00:33:23.292
There's a Prioress there

386
00:33:23.294 --> 00:33:25.421
who's older
than anyone remembers...

387
00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:28.383
she has healing magic.

388
00:33:29.885 --> 00:33:31.635
I'll take you to her.

389
00:33:31.637 --> 00:33:33.471
She'll get you well again.

390
00:33:34.430 --> 00:33:36.517
I've heard incredible stories.

391
00:33:38.184 --> 00:33:40.353
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

392
00:33:48.862 --> 00:33:50.822
(WAVES SPLASHING)

393
00:34:21.603 --> 00:34:23.605
(WIND BLOWING)

394
00:34:31.780 --> 00:34:33.281
(BANGING)

395
00:34:33.990 --> 00:34:36.159
(BREATHING SHALLOW)

396
00:34:37.452 --> 00:34:40.371
Robin. we must leave you.

397
00:34:41.873 --> 00:34:43.208
They'll be hunting us.

398
00:34:44.918 --> 00:34:46.878
(INDISTINCT WHISPERING)

399
00:34:49.089 --> 00:34:51.299
(CONTINUES
BREATHING SHALLOW)

400
00:34:56.847 --> 00:34:58.389
(SILENCE)

401
00:35:20.161 --> 00:35:21.622
WOMAN: (ECHOING)
Look at the snow...

402
00:35:24.625 --> 00:35:26.459
it's strange
for it to fall this late.

403
00:35:30.589 --> 00:35:32.423
But it won't stay
on the ground...

404
00:35:35.552 --> 00:35:37.387
and the long days
will soon some.

405
00:35:43.434 --> 00:35:45.979
(GASPS. GROANS)

406
00:35:48.273 --> 00:35:50.358
(SEAGULLS CALLING)

407
00:35:53.319 --> 00:35:55.488
(EXHALES)

408
00:35:57.282 --> 00:35:58.700
(GRUNTS)

409
00:36:02.078 --> 00:36:04.080
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

410
00:36:16.552 --> 00:36:17.969
(DOOR CLOSES)

411
00:36:30.315 --> 00:36:31.733
WOMAN:
A man brought you here.

412
00:36:33.276 --> 00:36:34.734
He sealed
your wounds with fire

413
00:36:34.736 --> 00:36:36.780
-and he did not do a poor job.
-(GROANS SOFTLY)

414
00:36:38.364 --> 00:36:39.950
You have been here six days.

415
00:36:41.451 --> 00:36:43.161
You have wounds
in your abdomen.

416
00:36:44.245 --> 00:36:46.623
Ribs and a leg badly broken.

417
00:36:48.709 --> 00:36:50.711
Do you understand my words?

418
00:36:54.965 --> 00:36:56.923
Where is this?

419
00:36:56.925 --> 00:36:59.175
WOMAN: You're at
the Priory of St. Clement.

420
00:36:59.177 --> 00:37:00.596
We're a place for you to heal.

421
00:37:01.555 --> 00:37:03.181
Wha... What town?

422
00:37:04.182 --> 00:37:05.517
There is no town.

423
00:37:07.268 --> 00:37:09.020
Do you know the story of Saul?

424
00:37:11.147 --> 00:37:12.480
What?

425
00:37:12.482 --> 00:37:15.650
It goes. there once
was a man. Saul...

426
00:37:15.652 --> 00:37:18.989
a breather of menaces
against disciples of the Lord.

427
00:37:19.823 --> 00:37:21.656
He came
to the Prince of Priests

428
00:37:21.658 --> 00:37:24.075
and asked of him
letters into Damascus.

429
00:37:24.077 --> 00:37:25.493
to the synagogues.

430
00:37:25.495 --> 00:37:26.870
That if he came across

431
00:37:26.872 --> 00:37:28.788
any man or woman of this life.
he should lead them bound

432
00:37:28.790 --> 00:37:30.166
-and...
-(ROBIN GRUNTS)

433
00:37:31.585 --> 00:37:33.587
That is all we need to do.

434
00:37:34.713 --> 00:37:36.256
-Just a few drops.
-(BLOOD DRIPPING)

435
00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:40.594
It was not too painful?

436
00:37:42.638 --> 00:37:43.889
It were not.

437
00:37:48.393 --> 00:37:49.686
I'm Sister Brigid.

438
00:37:51.104 --> 00:37:52.523
What's your name?

439
00:37:54.399 --> 00:37:55.609
Randolph.

440
00:37:59.905 --> 00:38:02.574
Well. I owe you
an apology. Randolph.

441
00:38:03.408 --> 00:38:04.910
What apology?

442
00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:08.789
You begged for me
to let you die.

443
00:38:10.791 --> 00:38:12.083
And I did not.

444
00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:15.544
You said it was right.

445
00:38:15.546 --> 00:38:16.797
I were with fever.

446
00:38:18.840 --> 00:38:20.634
Well. your fever has passed.

447
00:38:22.218 --> 00:38:23.303
Rest now. Randolph.

448
00:38:46.910 --> 00:38:50.038
MAN: Your body
is covered in scars.

449
00:38:50.706 --> 00:38:52.874
(ROBIN GASPING SOFTLY)

450
00:39:07.138 --> 00:39:09.474
Do you mean anyone
at this Priory harm?

451
00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:14.730
I do not.

452
00:39:24.948 --> 00:39:27.993
THE LEPER: Will any harm
follow you here?

453
00:39:29.828 --> 00:39:31.121
It will not.

454
00:39:40.296 --> 00:39:43.216
THE LEPER: (SOFTLY)
You will do them no harm.

455
00:39:57.397 --> 00:39:58.356
(DOOR CLOSES)

456
00:40:02.402 --> 00:40:03.945
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

457
00:40:15.373 --> 00:40:17.541
SISTER BRIGID:
Now back to the bed.

458
00:40:17.543 --> 00:40:20.170
(SLOW. LIMPING FOOTSTEPS)

459
00:40:24.966 --> 00:40:27.218
(ROBIN GRUNTING)

460
00:40:29.888 --> 00:40:31.557
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

461
00:40:32.724 --> 00:40:34.142
Now back to the door.

462
00:40:39.731 --> 00:40:41.900
(ROBIN GRUNTING)

463
00:41:02.295 --> 00:41:03.545
SISTER BRIGID:
Now open the door.

464
00:41:03.547 --> 00:41:05.131
(ROBIN BREATHING HEAVILY)

465
00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:13.640
(INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING)

466
00:41:22.816 --> 00:41:24.400
Go as far as you'd like.

467
00:41:27.863 --> 00:41:30.073
(CONTINUES BREATHING HEAVILY)

468
00:41:39.207 --> 00:41:41.417
(BREATHING HEAVILY. GRUNTING)

469
00:42:03.565 --> 00:42:05.441
(BIRD CHIRPING)

470
00:42:07.068 --> 00:42:09.237
(SERENE MUSIC PLAYING)

471
00:42:19.205 --> 00:42:21.374
(DISTANT ANIMAL CALLING)

472
00:42:30.551 --> 00:42:32.553
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

473
00:42:50.361 --> 00:42:52.573
(CHILDREN LAUGHING.
CHATTERING)

474
00:42:57.077 --> 00:42:59.287
(GOATS BLEATING)

475
00:43:06.002 --> 00:43:08.171
(CHATTERING CONTINUES)

476
00:43:12.425 --> 00:43:14.342
WOMAN: William.
careful. please.

477
00:43:14.344 --> 00:43:16.638
(BOY SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

478
00:43:18.849 --> 00:43:20.851
(GROANS. BREATHES HEAVILY)

479
00:43:22.519 --> 00:43:23.729
SISTER BRIGID:
Can you row yet?

480
00:43:26.565 --> 00:43:28.690
There is a boat
on the west shore.

481
00:43:28.692 --> 00:43:31.150
(PANTING)

482
00:43:31.152 --> 00:43:32.403
That's all right.

483
00:43:33.739 --> 00:43:36.239
You can stay here
if you help in the orchard.

484
00:43:36.241 --> 00:43:38.243
Oh. I'm... not a farmer.

485
00:43:39.119 --> 00:43:40.746
Then you know not how to hunt.

486
00:43:41.329 --> 00:43:42.789
Aye. I know how to hunt.

487
00:43:44.124 --> 00:43:47.000
There is some game
on this island.

488
00:43:47.002 --> 00:43:50.629
But no. you cannot hunt.
You cannot even draw a bow.

489
00:43:50.631 --> 00:43:52.881
-I can draw my bow.
-It's mostly rabbits.

490
00:43:52.883 --> 00:43:55.636
-Do you know how to trap?
-I know how to trap.

491
00:43:57.303 --> 00:43:59.470
Good. But no more
than six traps

492
00:43:59.472 --> 00:44:01.474
or the population
will not sustain.

493
00:44:02.183 --> 00:44:03.727
Can you manage six traps?

494
00:44:08.148 --> 00:44:09.608
I can manage six traps.

495
00:44:11.860 --> 00:44:12.903
Good.

496
00:44:14.195 --> 00:44:17.073
Then the rest of your time.
you may help in the orchard.

497
00:44:21.620 --> 00:44:23.997
-(WAVES SPLASHING)
-(SEAGULLS CALLING)

498
00:44:33.674 --> 00:44:34.675
(GRUNTS)

499
00:44:35.801 --> 00:44:36.843
(GROANS)

500
00:44:40.931 --> 00:44:42.348
(GRUNTS)

501
00:44:43.183 --> 00:44:45.101
(GROANS)

502
00:44:46.186 --> 00:44:47.938
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

503
00:44:53.527 --> 00:44:55.070
THE LEPER: Are you
trying to flee?

504
00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:00.534
You are quiet.

505
00:45:02.285 --> 00:45:04.454
THE LEPER: I am quiet
and slow.

506
00:45:05.789 --> 00:45:09.373
You are quiet.
but you need to be slow.

507
00:45:09.375 --> 00:45:10.542
You're a cripple.

508
00:45:10.544 --> 00:45:12.253
Aye. you're a leper.

509
00:45:13.171 --> 00:45:16.923
THE LEPER: It is all right
to be slow. We are safe here.

510
00:45:16.925 --> 00:45:19.593
ROBIN: That's quite a thing
to say. You know that?

511
00:45:19.595 --> 00:45:21.678
THE LEPER: I know that
because she has made us safe.

512
00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:23.056
ROBIN: Oh. your Prioress?

513
00:45:25.475 --> 00:45:26.768
THE LEPER: She were like us.

514
00:45:27.769 --> 00:45:31.857
She knew great sorrow.
Great pain.

515
00:45:32.608 --> 00:45:33.859
Widowed young.

516
00:45:36.069 --> 00:45:37.611
But through that sorrow.

517
00:45:37.613 --> 00:45:39.821
she found the strength
to heal us.

518
00:45:39.823 --> 00:45:42.448
Well. you do not look
like you've been healed.

519
00:45:42.450 --> 00:45:43.910
(THE LEPER CHUCKLES)

520
00:45:45.871 --> 00:45:47.704
The Prioress once told me
a story

521
00:45:47.706 --> 00:45:49.708
of a great philosopher...

522
00:45:50.834 --> 00:45:53.504
the greatest philosopher
of his time.

523
00:45:54.462 --> 00:45:57.881
But one day.
his king turned against him.

524
00:45:57.883 --> 00:46:00.969
Threw him in a dungeon
to be tortured and executed.

525
00:46:02.428 --> 00:46:04.513
But in his misery.

526
00:46:04.515 --> 00:46:07.641
when he had nothing.
an angel came

527
00:46:07.643 --> 00:46:09.895
to the philosopher
and she spoke to him.

528
00:46:11.021 --> 00:46:12.896
And from her.

529
00:46:12.898 --> 00:46:15.524
he learned
that it did not matter

530
00:46:15.526 --> 00:46:18.111
if this whole world
were misery...

531
00:46:19.863 --> 00:46:21.907
if all he had were death.

532
00:46:23.575 --> 00:46:25.617
Because he had one thing

533
00:46:25.619 --> 00:46:27.954
that could never be
touched or taken.

534
00:46:30.541 --> 00:46:31.875
He had his mind.

535
00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:34.961
And in his mind...

536
00:46:36.672 --> 00:46:38.006
he had God.

537
00:46:40.676 --> 00:46:44.220
It's never too late
to find peace. (GRUNTS)

538
00:46:45.180 --> 00:46:46.262
What are you doing?

539
00:46:46.264 --> 00:46:49.223
THE LEPER: (GROANS) Ah.
I row across every day.

540
00:46:49.225 --> 00:46:51.142
Your friend was strong enough
to take you.

541
00:46:51.144 --> 00:46:53.061
but some are not.
so I ferry them.

542
00:46:53.063 --> 00:46:55.980
-Will you take me across?
-I will not.

543
00:46:55.982 --> 00:46:59.108
You can row yourself
when you're stronger.

544
00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:01.986
For now. work at your tasks.
Trapping. I hear.

545
00:47:01.988 --> 00:47:04.240
-I will hunt.
-No. you can't hunt.

546
00:47:06.201 --> 00:47:07.786
(THE LEPER GRUNTS)

547
00:47:09.663 --> 00:47:11.287
ROBIN: Leper.

548
00:47:11.289 --> 00:47:13.709
what happened
to that great philosopher?

549
00:47:14.710 --> 00:47:17.713
He were tortured
and executed. of course.

550
00:47:19.214 --> 00:47:20.256
Of course.

551
00:47:25.596 --> 00:47:27.053
(LAUGHTER AND CHATTER)

552
00:47:27.055 --> 00:47:29.639
THE LEPER: ♪ Sumer is icumen
In loude sing cuccu! ♪

553
00:47:29.641 --> 00:47:32.016
♪ Groweth seed
and bloweth meed ♪

554
00:47:32.018 --> 00:47:34.185
♪ And springth the wode now ♪

555
00:47:34.187 --> 00:47:36.354
♪ Sing cuccu ♪

556
00:47:36.356 --> 00:47:39.733
♪ Ewe bleteth after lamb
Loweth after calve cow ♪

557
00:47:39.735 --> 00:47:41.903
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

558
00:48:18.857 --> 00:48:20.984
(MUSIC CONTINUES)

559
00:48:38.001 --> 00:48:40.211
(BREATHING SHARPLY)

560
00:48:43.799 --> 00:48:46.342
-(GRUNTING)
-(BOWSTRING STRETCHES)

561
00:48:48.344 --> 00:48:50.305
-(BOWSTRING TWANGS)
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)

562
00:48:53.809 --> 00:48:55.850
(GRUNTING)

563
00:48:55.852 --> 00:48:57.979
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

564
00:49:00.524 --> 00:49:01.525
(GROANS)

565
00:49:02.734 --> 00:49:04.402
(GRUNTING)

566
00:49:05.236 --> 00:49:06.945
-(GROANS)
-(ARROW THUDS)

567
00:49:06.947 --> 00:49:08.112
-(YELLS)
-(BOW CLATTERS)

568
00:49:08.114 --> 00:49:10.283
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

569
00:49:12.243 --> 00:49:14.120
(BOY YELLING INDISTINCTLY)

570
00:49:21.044 --> 00:49:23.336
ROBIN: Oi! Oi!

571
00:49:23.338 --> 00:49:25.381
The Leper has brought someone!

572
00:49:25.799 --> 00:49:27.551
From the far shore!

573
00:49:59.791 --> 00:50:01.251
(LITTLE MARGARET
BREATHES HEAVILY)

574
00:50:07.423 --> 00:50:08.759
LITTLE MARGARET: Papa's dead.

575
00:50:11.887 --> 00:50:13.555
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

576
00:50:33.158 --> 00:50:35.491
(GRASS RUSTLING)

577
00:50:35.493 --> 00:50:37.453
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

578
00:50:39.330 --> 00:50:41.499
(RABBIT'S LEGS THUMPING)

579
00:50:57.766 --> 00:50:59.518
(LEGS THUMPING FRANTICALLY)

580
00:51:02.437 --> 00:51:04.147
-(BONES CRACK)
-(THUMPING STOPS)

581
00:51:06.107 --> 00:51:07.693
(RECEDING FOOTSTEPS)

582
00:51:13.824 --> 00:51:14.908
(CROW CAWS)

583
00:51:17.035 --> 00:51:18.244
(ROBIN GROANS SOFTLY)

584
00:51:24.668 --> 00:51:26.211
How's the girl?

585
00:51:39.474 --> 00:51:41.476
THE LEPER: Let me show you
my trees.

586
00:51:51.570 --> 00:51:54.779
These are the elderberries.

587
00:51:54.781 --> 00:51:57.574
They harvest
late in the summer.

588
00:51:57.576 --> 00:51:59.868
ROBIN: Do they know
what you were before this?

589
00:51:59.870 --> 00:52:02.078
THE LEPER: Oh. you'll have
to favor this side

590
00:52:02.080 --> 00:52:03.248
for my hearing.

591
00:52:05.584 --> 00:52:08.336
Pears. I harvest just after.

592
00:52:11.422 --> 00:52:13.507
And what were I before this?

593
00:52:13.509 --> 00:52:15.258
ROBIN: Oh.
a sellsword at best.

594
00:52:15.260 --> 00:52:17.638
THE LEPER: (CHUCKLING)
Aye. at best. certainly.

595
00:52:18.555 --> 00:52:19.931
We have a way about us!

596
00:52:21.391 --> 00:52:22.891
You remember the trees?

597
00:52:22.893 --> 00:52:25.353
-Pears and elderberries.
-THE LEPER: Wonderful.

598
00:52:28.273 --> 00:52:29.566
Some of them know.

599
00:52:30.776 --> 00:52:33.987
But the Prioress does not care
who we were.

600
00:52:36.197 --> 00:52:38.659
And the apples harvest
in the autumn.

601
00:52:39.951 --> 00:52:43.038
ROBIN: Did she. uh.
speak of what happened to her?

602
00:52:44.706 --> 00:52:46.790
THE LEPER: Well. the Prioress
is tending to the girl.

603
00:52:46.792 --> 00:52:49.670
You should speak with her.
if you are concerned.

604
00:52:53.173 --> 00:52:54.424
What were the trees?

605
00:52:56.259 --> 00:52:58.679
ROBIN: Pears. apples
and elderberries.

606
00:53:00.597 --> 00:53:01.807
THE LEPER: Wonderful.

607
00:53:02.808 --> 00:53:03.809
(DOOR CLOSES)

608
00:53:13.569 --> 00:53:15.403
SISTER BRIGID: This will be
your last letting.

609
00:53:16.738 --> 00:53:18.949
Though your body
still has much healing.

610
00:53:22.828 --> 00:53:23.912
You're tired.

611
00:53:25.121 --> 00:53:26.164
I am.

612
00:53:27.457 --> 00:53:28.959
But I have been tired before.

613
00:53:31.169 --> 00:53:32.588
The child does not sleep.

614
00:53:36.132 --> 00:53:37.509
What happened to her?

615
00:53:39.135 --> 00:53:40.178
Terrible things.

616
00:53:43.431 --> 00:53:46.641
-She told you her story?
-No. she does not speak.

617
00:53:46.643 --> 00:53:48.895
She does not eat
and she does not sleep.

618
00:53:53.274 --> 00:53:55.527
-(SKIN PRICKS)
-(BLOOD DRIPPING)

619
00:53:56.486 --> 00:53:57.821
What is her name?

620
00:54:05.495 --> 00:54:06.747
Margaret.

621
00:54:09.875 --> 00:54:11.167
Who is she?

622
00:54:13.253 --> 00:54:16.172
I met her father. A farmer.

623
00:54:17.423 --> 00:54:19.215
SISTER BRIGID: Well.
he's dead.

624
00:54:19.217 --> 00:54:20.299
It seems.

625
00:54:20.301 --> 00:54:21.760
And the mother?

626
00:54:21.762 --> 00:54:24.638
-Ah. I think dead.
-How?

627
00:54:24.640 --> 00:54:26.725
I don't know. Dead past.

628
00:54:27.893 --> 00:54:28.894
Slain?

629
00:54:30.145 --> 00:54:31.187
Perhaps.

630
00:54:36.610 --> 00:54:37.986
You lie very well.

631
00:54:39.154 --> 00:54:40.822
(BLOOD STOPS DRIPPING)

632
00:54:47.453 --> 00:54:48.747
Did the child see?

633
00:54:51.374 --> 00:54:52.834
She could have.

634
00:54:55.420 --> 00:54:57.172
That is much
for a child to see.

635
00:55:00.133 --> 00:55:01.342
(SIGHS)

636
00:55:07.390 --> 00:55:08.850
I'm sorry for your friend.

637
00:55:13.438 --> 00:55:14.648
Thank you.

638
00:55:15.899 --> 00:55:18.109
Would you like me
to pray for him?

639
00:55:22.322 --> 00:55:23.740
As you wish.

640
00:55:27.285 --> 00:55:28.411
What was his name?

641
00:55:33.083 --> 00:55:34.167
Edward.

642
00:55:36.419 --> 00:55:37.713
SISTER BRIGID: Edward.

643
00:55:40.841 --> 00:55:42.423
Be not your heart afraid.

644
00:55:42.425 --> 00:55:43.675
for ye believe in God

645
00:55:43.677 --> 00:55:45.011
and ye believe in me.

646
00:55:46.930 --> 00:55:49.766
In the house of my father.
there are many rooms.

647
00:55:51.059 --> 00:55:54.143
And when I make ready
for you a place.

648
00:55:54.145 --> 00:55:56.481
I shall come
and take thee to myself.

649
00:55:57.858 --> 00:56:00.861
For where I am.
He may be also.

650
00:56:03.238 --> 00:56:05.448
And whither I go.
He shall know the way.

651
00:56:08.660 --> 00:56:10.328
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

652
00:56:11.454 --> 00:56:13.832
(BOY SCREAMING. CRYING LOUDLY)

653
00:56:17.293 --> 00:56:19.505
(BOY CONTINUES SCREAMING
AND CRYING)

654
00:56:26.595 --> 00:56:28.469
-THE LEPER: She has a knife.
-SISTER BRIGID: Margaret!

655
00:56:28.471 --> 00:56:29.888
She stabbed me!

656
00:56:29.890 --> 00:56:31.391
SISTER BRIGID: Margaret!

657
00:56:33.727 --> 00:56:35.769
-(BOY CONTINUES CRYING)
-It's all right.

658
00:56:35.771 --> 00:56:36.936
(LITTLE MARGARET
BREATHING HEAVILY)

659
00:56:36.938 --> 00:56:39.147
Margaret. it's...
it's all right.

660
00:56:39.149 --> 00:56:41.026
-Margaret. it's all right.
-(LITTLE MARGARET CRIES)

661
00:56:43.987 --> 00:56:45.695
THE LEPER: She don't know
this island.

662
00:56:45.697 --> 00:56:47.407
There are boar about.

663
00:56:49.075 --> 00:56:50.449
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

664
00:56:50.451 --> 00:56:52.035
-THE LEPER: Margaret!
-SISTER BRIGID: Margaret!

665
00:56:52.037 --> 00:56:53.870
-(WIND BLOWING)
-SISTER BRIGID: Margaret!

666
00:56:53.872 --> 00:56:56.790
-WOMAN: Margaret!
-SISTER BRIGID: Margaret!

667
00:56:56.792 --> 00:56:58.334
WOMAN: Margaret!

668
00:57:00.420 --> 00:57:02.380
(WIND WHOOSHING)

669
00:57:04.633 --> 00:57:06.426
(FOREBODING MUSIC PLAYING)

670
00:57:28.907 --> 00:57:30.534
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

671
00:57:55.851 --> 00:57:58.103
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

672
00:58:29.050 --> 00:58:30.218
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

673
00:58:44.065 --> 00:58:45.275
Oi.

674
00:58:47.861 --> 00:58:48.904
Oi!

675
00:58:49.362 --> 00:58:51.156
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

676
00:58:57.579 --> 00:58:58.747
Give it.

677
00:59:09.049 --> 00:59:10.509
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

678
00:59:12.177 --> 00:59:13.428
Give it.

679
00:59:30.821 --> 00:59:32.488
Those men that hurt you.

680
00:59:35.784 --> 00:59:36.827
do they know you're here?

681
00:59:42.583 --> 00:59:43.584
Hmm.

682
00:59:50.340 --> 00:59:51.717
What's my name?

683
00:59:57.889 --> 00:59:58.890
Say my name.

684
01:00:01.101 --> 01:00:02.352
Randolph.

685
01:00:06.022 --> 01:00:07.398
(SIGHS)

686
01:00:08.066 --> 01:00:09.317
That's right.

687
01:00:14.489 --> 01:00:16.241
Who's Little John?

688
01:00:18.451 --> 01:00:21.745
That name is nonsense
and you should never speak it.

689
01:00:21.747 --> 01:00:24.372
And if you speak it.
a cat will come in the night

690
01:00:24.374 --> 01:00:25.498
and take your tongue.

691
01:00:25.500 --> 01:00:27.669
(BREATH TREMBLING)

692
01:00:33.008 --> 01:00:34.009
(SIGHS)

693
01:00:35.927 --> 01:00:37.012
It's all right.

694
01:00:40.098 --> 01:00:41.307
Go to sleep.

695
01:00:43.476 --> 01:00:45.646
(WIND WHISTLING)

696
01:00:48.649 --> 01:00:49.983
ROBIN: I'll watch the storm.

697
01:00:54.404 --> 01:00:56.489
All right. lay down.

698
01:01:00.326 --> 01:01:01.578
Close your eyes.

699
01:01:06.792 --> 01:01:07.834
You can sleep.

700
01:01:13.089 --> 01:01:14.382
Sleep.

701
01:01:52.879 --> 01:01:55.048
SISTER BRIGID: Thank you
for bringing her back.

702
01:01:57.425 --> 01:01:58.677
It were nothing.

703
01:02:04.015 --> 01:02:06.101
Do you know the story
of this Priory?

704
01:02:07.185 --> 01:02:08.436
ROBIN: No.

705
01:02:10.772 --> 01:02:12.689
Well. in ages before history.

706
01:02:12.691 --> 01:02:14.315
this was a holy site

707
01:02:14.317 --> 01:02:15.861
of the ancient Druids.

708
01:02:17.863 --> 01:02:19.781
They worshipped unknown gods.

709
01:02:21.491 --> 01:02:22.993
Worshipped in these woods.

710
01:02:24.578 --> 01:02:27.078
Then the Romans came long ago.
and they sensed

711
01:02:27.080 --> 01:02:28.412
the magic of this place.

712
01:02:28.414 --> 01:02:30.083
so they built their temples.

713
01:02:31.960 --> 01:02:33.752
And people upon people
sensed it.

714
01:02:33.754 --> 01:02:35.756
and they came here to worship.

715
01:02:37.340 --> 01:02:39.090
Countless gods.
tribe after tribe.

716
01:02:39.092 --> 01:02:41.928
who would not even know
how to speak to each other.

717
01:02:43.096 --> 01:02:45.306
Yet we were all
pulled to this place.

718
01:02:47.392 --> 01:02:50.020
ROBIN: Do you believe
there is magic in this island?

719
01:02:52.523 --> 01:02:54.190
I believe there is power
in it.

720
01:02:57.027 --> 01:02:59.237
I have seen
the power in stories.

721
01:03:01.907 --> 01:03:05.201
They can be used to make men
do terrible things.

722
01:03:06.286 --> 01:03:10.248
And then those terrible things
become stories.

723
01:03:11.583 --> 01:03:12.793
And stories...

724
01:03:17.130 --> 01:03:18.131
No.

725
01:03:18.840 --> 01:03:20.341
You cannot trust any of them.

726
01:03:21.342 --> 01:03:23.178
We cannot be
trusted with them.

727
01:03:25.556 --> 01:03:28.349
Knives cut bread
as well as they do flesh.

728
01:03:30.060 --> 01:03:31.728
It's a question of balance.

729
01:03:32.604 --> 01:03:34.314
ROBIN: Does balance
have a say?

730
01:03:36.858 --> 01:03:39.277
I think if balance
did not have some say.

731
01:03:40.486 --> 01:03:41.947
we would not be here.

732
01:03:44.074 --> 01:03:47.911
This world would not...
be here and...

733
01:03:49.245 --> 01:03:51.372
we would not be
sharing these words.

734
01:03:52.541 --> 01:03:53.959
And do you ever consider that?

735
01:03:56.086 --> 01:03:57.794
The incredible precision
of balance

736
01:03:57.796 --> 01:04:00.298
over such an expanse of time.

737
01:04:01.925 --> 01:04:06.177
The balance it takes to create
a word. any specific word.

738
01:04:06.179 --> 01:04:09.015
That can pass
between lips and...

739
01:04:10.851 --> 01:04:13.144
be understood by two minds.

740
01:04:20.569 --> 01:04:21.862
Randolph.

741
01:04:25.782 --> 01:04:27.075
Thank you.

742
01:05:08.659 --> 01:05:09.826
(ROBIN GRUNTS)

743
01:05:32.808 --> 01:05:34.601
-ROBIN: Mmm. Mmm.
-SISTER BRIGID: Mmm.

744
01:05:46.321 --> 01:05:47.363
Not hungry?

745
01:05:49.324 --> 01:05:50.491
No?

746
01:06:23.233 --> 01:06:24.735
THE LEPER: I'll be dying soon.

747
01:06:26.570 --> 01:06:27.613
ROBIN: How do you know?

748
01:06:30.031 --> 01:06:31.992
THE LEPER: I can
feel it inside.

749
01:06:34.369 --> 01:06:36.204
ROBIN: What does it feel like?

750
01:06:38.331 --> 01:06:40.000
THE LEPER: It feels right.

751
01:06:43.920 --> 01:06:46.089
(SEAGULL SQUAWKING)

752
01:06:51.595 --> 01:06:53.138
There's someone there.

753
01:06:56.141 --> 01:06:57.768
THE LEPER: The waters
have been busy.

754
01:07:01.229 --> 01:07:02.523
ROBIN: Start around the feet.

755
01:07:03.023 --> 01:07:04.232
Little cuts.

756
01:07:04.691 --> 01:07:05.734
Good. Other one.

757
01:07:07.986 --> 01:07:10.238
All right. Oh.

758
01:07:11.907 --> 01:07:13.116
(SOFTLY) Okay.

759
01:07:13.992 --> 01:07:15.575
Good.

760
01:07:15.577 --> 01:07:17.326
Right. now.
let's do down the front.

761
01:07:17.328 --> 01:07:19.122
Right down on the belly. Good.

762
01:07:20.123 --> 01:07:22.165
Right. Give me.

763
01:07:22.167 --> 01:07:24.125
Right. Watch this one.

764
01:07:24.127 --> 01:07:26.878
Just like... just like that.

765
01:07:26.880 --> 01:07:28.549
That's it.
You do the other one.

766
01:07:30.008 --> 01:07:32.383
That's it. that's it.
that's it.

767
01:07:32.385 --> 01:07:33.386
Pull.

768
01:07:36.389 --> 01:07:38.559
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

769
01:07:44.355 --> 01:07:46.525
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

770
01:07:51.613 --> 01:07:53.406
(SISTER BRIGID
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

771
01:08:08.922 --> 01:08:11.216
SISTER BRIGID: You are a brave
young man.

772
01:08:12.217 --> 01:08:13.552
ARTHUR: Thank you. sister.

773
01:08:15.428 --> 01:08:16.805
Are you hungry. Arthur?

774
01:08:17.723 --> 01:08:20.765
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

775
01:08:20.767 --> 01:08:22.308
I am. sister.

776
01:08:22.310 --> 01:08:24.978
Well. Sarah will fix you up
a good supper tonight.

777
01:08:24.980 --> 01:08:27.357
Herring stew. Herring stew.

778
01:08:29.275 --> 01:08:32.235
-Do you like that?
-Yes.

779
01:08:32.237 --> 01:08:33.655
Where do you come from.
Arthur?

780
01:08:37.492 --> 01:08:39.200
My family farm
toward Keswick.

781
01:08:39.202 --> 01:08:41.369
-ROBIN: Toward Keswick?
-Yes. Sir.

782
01:08:41.371 --> 01:08:44.288
-Randolph
-Randolph. Toward Keswick.

783
01:08:44.290 --> 01:08:46.292
The Leper said
you seek your niece.

784
01:08:47.168 --> 01:08:48.670
-I do.
-You were set upon?

785
01:08:51.089 --> 01:08:52.633
-I was.
-On the road?

786
01:08:54.551 --> 01:08:55.800
Yes.

787
01:08:55.802 --> 01:08:57.554
-You are safe here.
-Which road?

788
01:08:59.430 --> 01:09:00.891
The road to Keswick. Sir.

789
01:09:02.475 --> 01:09:04.225
Thank the Lord you survived.

790
01:09:04.227 --> 01:09:05.602
I do thank the Lord.

791
01:09:05.604 --> 01:09:07.436
How about honeyed pears
after supper

792
01:09:07.438 --> 01:09:08.899
for being so brave?

793
01:09:12.068 --> 01:09:14.320
-Thank you. sister.
-Good.

794
01:09:27.793 --> 01:09:29.044
Little Margaret.

795
01:09:30.420 --> 01:09:31.961
That man. Arthur.

796
01:09:31.963 --> 01:09:34.800
Did you ever see him
before you came to the Priory?

797
01:09:38.053 --> 01:09:39.054
Margaret.

798
01:09:46.603 --> 01:09:50.065
The men...
The men who hurt your papa.

799
01:09:52.943 --> 01:09:54.570
Did you see their faces?

800
01:09:55.862 --> 01:09:57.405
Papa said to run.

801
01:09:58.574 --> 01:09:59.908
(LITTLE MARGARET SIGHS)

802
01:10:08.291 --> 01:10:09.626
Papa stopped praying.

803
01:10:11.419 --> 01:10:12.544
He was angry.

804
01:10:12.546 --> 01:10:14.170
(SIGHS. MUTTERS)

805
01:10:14.172 --> 01:10:15.591
He prayed in his mind.

806
01:10:19.010 --> 01:10:20.011
What's Papa's name?

807
01:10:22.514 --> 01:10:23.682
(ARROW THUDS)

808
01:10:24.390 --> 01:10:25.726
Your papa's your papa.

809
01:10:38.446 --> 01:10:39.656
Bring it here.

810
01:10:41.742 --> 01:10:42.909
(ROBIN GRUNTS SOFTLY)

811
01:10:49.249 --> 01:10:51.209
Oh. this is fine work.

812
01:10:55.338 --> 01:10:56.715
Oh.

813
01:10:57.257 --> 01:10:59.009
You see it favors
a bend here.

814
01:11:00.719 --> 01:11:04.472
Oh. aye. Now you have to
balance it so it bends evenly.

815
01:11:05.306 --> 01:11:09.102
So this part here needs
to be thinned. All right?

816
01:11:14.525 --> 01:11:15.984
Can you make for me?

817
01:11:18.862 --> 01:11:20.280
You want me
to make you a bow?

818
01:11:25.035 --> 01:11:26.077
All right.

819
01:11:27.453 --> 01:11:28.664
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

820
01:11:34.127 --> 01:11:35.669
SISTER BRIGID: Today.
I remembered a story

821
01:11:35.671 --> 01:11:38.046
by a poet named Lucretius.

822
01:11:38.048 --> 01:11:39.132
(FIRE CRACKLES)

823
01:11:40.008 --> 01:11:42.010
He wrote on
what are called atoms.

824
01:11:43.804 --> 01:11:45.762
Where if you pick apart
the trees

825
01:11:45.764 --> 01:11:47.597
and people and stones.

826
01:11:47.599 --> 01:11:51.059
these would be the smallest
invisible pieces

827
01:11:51.061 --> 01:11:54.648
that make up
everything in creation.

828
01:11:56.525 --> 01:12:00.987
And these atoms are sailing
through the void and...

829
01:12:03.824 --> 01:12:05.657
well. sometimes.
for no reason at all.

830
01:12:05.659 --> 01:12:06.993
they change their course.

831
01:12:09.996 --> 01:12:12.207
The least amount.
not even a hair.

832
01:12:17.087 --> 01:12:20.966
And if it weren't
for that small...

833
01:12:21.800 --> 01:12:25.802
unpredictable change
forcing the atoms to cross

834
01:12:25.804 --> 01:12:27.764
and weave with each other...

835
01:12:30.934 --> 01:12:33.770
nothing at all
under the heavens would exist.

836
01:12:35.522 --> 01:12:37.023
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

837
01:13:26.447 --> 01:13:27.824
(INCENSE SIZZLES)

838
01:13:29.993 --> 01:13:32.871
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

839
01:13:42.338 --> 01:13:44.049
(EXHALES)

840
01:13:44.966 --> 01:13:47.511
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

841
01:13:54.059 --> 01:13:56.269
(MOANING SOFTLY)

842
01:14:28.927 --> 01:14:31.555
(GASPING SOFTLY)

843
01:14:37.393 --> 01:14:39.437
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

844
01:14:40.021 --> 01:14:41.189
(MOANS AND GASPS)

845
01:14:57.413 --> 01:14:59.165
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

846
01:15:17.893 --> 01:15:19.934
ROBIN: Yes. Good.

847
01:15:19.936 --> 01:15:21.354
-(CHUCKLES)
-Harder.

848
01:15:21.980 --> 01:15:23.271
That's it. Good.

849
01:15:23.273 --> 01:15:26.608
-(LAUGHS)
-(CHUCKLES)

850
01:15:26.610 --> 01:15:28.820
That's good. Harder.

851
01:15:29.738 --> 01:15:31.195
Let me help you.

852
01:15:31.197 --> 01:15:32.697
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

853
01:15:32.699 --> 01:15:33.700
ROBIN: Grab that one.

854
01:15:34.993 --> 01:15:37.287
Good. There we go!

855
01:15:37.621 --> 01:15:38.662
(CHUCKLES) Good.

856
01:15:38.664 --> 01:15:40.666
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

857
01:15:42.125 --> 01:15:43.669
Which one do you think
for your bow?

858
01:15:44.545 --> 01:15:45.796
(MUMBLES) Let's hold and look.

859
01:15:46.755 --> 01:15:47.756
Okay.

860
01:15:48.549 --> 01:15:50.674
There we go.
They're both good.

861
01:15:50.676 --> 01:15:51.843
(LITTLE MARGARET
SIGHS CONTENTEDLY)

862
01:15:53.136 --> 01:15:54.555
(CHATTER CONTINUES)

863
01:16:01.978 --> 01:16:03.728
BOY: Margaret!

864
01:16:03.730 --> 01:16:05.354
Margaret! Come and play!

865
01:16:05.356 --> 01:16:07.568
(CHILDREN CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY)

866
01:16:11.738 --> 01:16:14.490
(CHILDREN LAUGHING
AND CHATTERING)

867
01:16:26.878 --> 01:16:28.839
(OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING)

868
01:16:33.343 --> 01:16:34.928
(CHATTER CONTINUES)

869
01:16:45.814 --> 01:16:46.815
ROBIN: Arthur.

870
01:16:48.191 --> 01:16:49.774
Do you know how to trap?

871
01:16:49.776 --> 01:16:51.484
-Yes.
-Good.

872
01:16:51.486 --> 01:16:53.530
I need a strong hand. Come.

873
01:17:06.668 --> 01:17:08.336
ROBIN:
Does your family have land?

874
01:17:10.046 --> 01:17:11.006
Yes.

875
01:17:13.091 --> 01:17:14.510
ROBIN: How many
of you are there?

876
01:17:16.512 --> 01:17:17.763
ARTHUR: I don't know.

877
01:17:21.016 --> 01:17:22.601
(GRUNTS. GROANS)

878
01:17:24.686 --> 01:17:25.937
-ARTHUR: Are you all right?
-(SIGHS)

879
01:17:27.731 --> 01:17:29.355
I am. I am.

880
01:17:29.357 --> 01:17:31.359
Just not as young
as I once were.

881
01:17:32.778 --> 01:17:34.027
(SIGHS)

882
01:17:34.029 --> 01:17:35.614
I could use a hand up is all.

883
01:17:37.783 --> 01:17:39.450
(GRUNTS. GROANS)

884
01:17:40.451 --> 01:17:41.662
Thank you.

885
01:17:43.288 --> 01:17:45.331
Oh aye. they delivered you
quite a blow.

886
01:17:47.333 --> 01:17:48.585
-Yes.
-Who did it?

887
01:17:51.254 --> 01:17:52.506
A man.

888
01:17:52.964 --> 01:17:54.007
Some men.

889
01:17:55.216 --> 01:17:57.093
-Bandits.
-A man. bandits?

890
01:17:58.219 --> 01:17:59.888
-Yes.
-Huh. May I look?

891
01:18:04.142 --> 01:18:05.143
(ROBIN INHALES SHARPLY)

892
01:18:06.019 --> 01:18:07.894
It's quite a blow.

893
01:18:07.896 --> 01:18:11.397
Oh. you're lucky you survived.
You're a lucky boy.

894
01:18:11.399 --> 01:18:12.481
Yes.

895
01:18:12.483 --> 01:18:14.776
You should be thankful
to be alive.

896
01:18:14.778 --> 01:18:17.072
-Yes.
-He used a quarterstaff?

897
01:18:23.369 --> 01:18:24.744
Hmm.

898
01:18:24.746 --> 01:18:26.665
Lucky it didn't
take your head off.

899
01:18:29.960 --> 01:18:31.417
(ROBIN SIGHS)

900
01:18:31.419 --> 01:18:33.088
BOY: (IN DISTANCE)
Randolph.

901
01:18:35.841 --> 01:18:37.092
Randolph.

902
01:18:40.136 --> 01:18:41.179
(SHOUTS) Moshe?

903
01:18:44.766 --> 01:18:47.477
The Prioress said to come.

904
01:18:48.186 --> 01:18:49.771
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

905
01:18:54.610 --> 01:18:56.778
(THE LEPER BREATHES WEAKLY)

906
01:19:24.097 --> 01:19:25.265
(WHEEZES)

907
01:19:29.019 --> 01:19:31.229
-Are you in great pain?
-(THE LEPER GROANS)

908
01:19:36.484 --> 01:19:37.778
(GROANS)

909
01:19:40.405 --> 01:19:42.282
Do you remember the trees?

910
01:19:44.910 --> 01:19:46.912
Pears. apples
and elderberries.

911
01:19:49.497 --> 01:19:50.749
Wonderful.

912
01:19:52.668 --> 01:19:53.919
(BREATHING HOARSELY)

913
01:19:57.338 --> 01:19:58.590
(GROANS)

914
01:20:01.176 --> 01:20:04.385
You know that you are
the most important person

915
01:20:04.387 --> 01:20:06.181
in Little Margaret's life.

916
01:20:06.765 --> 01:20:09.726
Ah. I'm not important.

917
01:20:10.351 --> 01:20:11.352
(THE LEPER GROANS)

918
01:20:17.275 --> 01:20:18.234
(GROANS)

919
01:20:22.405 --> 01:20:23.988
Think of all the people

920
01:20:23.990 --> 01:20:25.909
whose lives you've crossed.

921
01:20:27.327 --> 01:20:29.077
(THE LEPER GROANS)

922
01:20:29.079 --> 01:20:31.873
We were important somehow
to all of them.

923
01:20:39.297 --> 01:20:42.425
Do you know the story
of Guy of Gisborne

924
01:20:44.595 --> 01:20:46.137
and Robin Hood?

925
01:20:51.392 --> 01:20:52.686
Yes.

926
01:20:57.524 --> 01:20:59.860
They say you killed him.

927
01:21:00.652 --> 01:21:01.818
(THE LEPER GROANS)

928
01:21:01.820 --> 01:21:03.361
Did you really behead him?

929
01:21:03.363 --> 01:21:06.742
-You are confused. leper.
-Well. I'll not tell a soul.

930
01:21:09.285 --> 01:21:12.288
But don't lie to a man
on his deathbed.

931
01:21:14.875 --> 01:21:18.461
So. did you really behead him?

932
01:21:22.007 --> 01:21:24.340
There were no Guy of Gisborne.

933
01:21:24.342 --> 01:21:27.428
It were just one of the many
tales that passed along.

934
01:21:29.806 --> 01:21:31.391
But I beheaded other men.

935
01:21:34.269 --> 01:21:35.896
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

936
01:21:39.107 --> 01:21:41.109
You really don't remember?

937
01:21:42.402 --> 01:21:43.652
(THE LEPER SCOFFS SOFTLY)

938
01:21:43.654 --> 01:21:45.945
No. (SNORTS. GULPS)

939
01:21:45.947 --> 01:21:47.490
Think about that name.

940
01:21:52.162 --> 01:21:54.540
There were a Guy of Gisborne.

941
01:21:56.041 --> 01:21:57.208
(THE LEPER SIGHS)

942
01:21:58.501 --> 01:22:00.211
But you did not behead him.

943
01:22:02.964 --> 01:22:04.382
You cut off his ear.

944
01:22:08.595 --> 01:22:10.556
(SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING)

945
01:22:12.223 --> 01:22:17.310
You said. in another life.
you'd share a drink with him.

946
01:22:17.312 --> 01:22:18.522
(WHEEZES)

947
01:22:19.648 --> 01:22:21.024
Do you remember that?

948
01:22:33.078 --> 01:22:36.289
We seem to have
found another life.

949
01:22:39.835 --> 01:22:41.044
(SIGHS)

950
01:22:43.254 --> 01:22:46.172
THE LEPER: Now.
there is one cruelty

951
01:22:46.174 --> 01:22:48.758
I would ask you
to not bring about.

952
01:22:48.760 --> 01:22:51.177
(WHEEZES)

953
01:22:51.179 --> 01:22:53.221
(BREATHING WEAKLY) You will
guard the orchard

954
01:22:53.223 --> 01:22:55.475
until you too die.

955
01:22:58.687 --> 01:23:00.939
You will serve the Prioress...

956
01:23:02.440 --> 01:23:06.069
and the people of this Priory.
past and future.

957
01:23:10.866 --> 01:23:14.578
But at no point
in that time...

958
01:23:17.288 --> 01:23:21.543
in those
good and peaceful years.

959
01:23:24.588 --> 01:23:28.006
will you tell the Prioress
who you really are.

960
01:23:28.008 --> 01:23:29.173
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

961
01:23:29.175 --> 01:23:31.344
(SOMBER MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

962
01:23:34.515 --> 01:23:35.557
Why?

963
01:23:37.976 --> 01:23:39.227
Because...

964
01:23:41.021 --> 01:23:43.021
one of those nameless.

965
01:23:43.023 --> 01:23:44.313
faceless deaths

966
01:23:44.315 --> 01:23:46.359
in the shadows of your mind...

967
01:23:49.320 --> 01:23:51.072
were in another life...

968
01:23:53.909 --> 01:23:55.326
her beloved.

969
01:23:56.369 --> 01:23:58.539
(THE LEPER CONTINUES
BREATHING WEAKLY)

970
01:24:03.794 --> 01:24:04.836
Promise me.

971
01:24:10.133 --> 01:24:11.342
Robin...

972
01:24:13.094 --> 01:24:14.345
Promise me.

973
01:24:19.976 --> 01:24:22.187
(TENDER MUSIC PLAYING)

974
01:24:41.707 --> 01:24:49.253
WOMAN: ♪ Sumer is icumen in
Loude sing cuccu! ♪

975
01:24:49.255 --> 01:24:52.465
♪ Groweth seed
and bloweth meed ♪

976
01:24:52.467 --> 01:24:56.135
♪ And springth the wode now ♪

977
01:24:56.137 --> 01:24:59.764
♪ Sing cuccu ♪

978
01:24:59.766 --> 01:25:06.229
♪ Ewe bleteth after lamb
Loweth after calve cow ♪

979
01:25:06.231 --> 01:25:10.066
♪ Bulloc sterteth
bucke verteth ♪

980
01:25:10.068 --> 01:25:12.944
♪ Merye sing cuccu! ♪

981
01:25:12.946 --> 01:25:19.534
♪ Cuccu. cuccu
Wel singest thou cuccu! ♪

982
01:25:19.536 --> 01:25:21.578
♪ Ne swik thou never now! ♪

983
01:25:21.580 --> 01:25:23.790
-(SONG FADES)
-(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

984
01:25:29.963 --> 01:25:31.923
(SENTIMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

985
01:25:42.100 --> 01:25:43.852
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

986
01:25:46.396 --> 01:25:47.773
ROBIN: (WHISPERS)
Good-bye. Brigid.

987
01:25:57.908 --> 01:25:59.034
(FIRE CRACKLES)

988
01:26:01.327 --> 01:26:02.495
ROBIN: Arthur.

989
01:26:04.873 --> 01:26:05.957
Come.

990
01:26:07.042 --> 01:26:09.125
(BOAT CREAKING)

991
01:26:09.127 --> 01:26:10.879
There's a child
on the far shore.

992
01:26:12.506 --> 01:26:13.882
Perhaps it's your niece.

993
01:26:15.967 --> 01:26:18.094
The Leper said
you sought your lost niece.

994
01:26:19.888 --> 01:26:21.638
Yes.

995
01:26:21.640 --> 01:26:24.100
-Could it be her?
-We shall see.

996
01:26:26.311 --> 01:26:28.479
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

997
01:27:03.515 --> 01:27:05.517
I do not see signs of anyone.

998
01:27:06.727 --> 01:27:08.061
Ah. we should wait.

999
01:27:09.062 --> 01:27:10.480
Maybe they will return.

1000
01:27:32.711 --> 01:27:33.962
What is your name?

1001
01:27:38.133 --> 01:27:39.217
Arthur.

1002
01:27:40.552 --> 01:27:42.677
Do not waste time lying to me.

1003
01:27:42.679 --> 01:27:43.930
What is your real name?

1004
01:27:45.682 --> 01:27:47.308
(BREATH TREMBLES)

1005
01:27:48.894 --> 01:27:49.978
Godwyn.

1006
01:27:53.273 --> 01:27:55.690
You are deciding. Godwyn.

1007
01:27:55.692 --> 01:27:57.861
whether to do
the deed yourself...

1008
01:27:59.154 --> 01:28:00.656
or to fetch your family.

1009
01:28:04.075 --> 01:28:05.033
What deed?

1010
01:28:05.035 --> 01:28:07.203
How many men
have you killed. Godwyn?

1011
01:28:08.705 --> 01:28:11.455
How many children
have you killed?

1012
01:28:11.457 --> 01:28:13.669
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1013
01:28:16.838 --> 01:28:19.925
I have killed so many.
I could not give you a count.

1014
01:28:21.677 --> 01:28:23.552
For longer than
you've been alive.

1015
01:28:23.554 --> 01:28:26.555
I've been killing the kin of
those I killed a lifetime ago.

1016
01:28:26.557 --> 01:28:28.598
I do not remember the first.

1017
01:28:28.600 --> 01:28:30.894
who meant nothing to me
at the time. but...

1018
01:28:32.145 --> 01:28:34.187
their brothers
and their children.

1019
01:28:34.189 --> 01:28:36.817
their grandchildren.
they remember me.

1020
01:28:37.776 --> 01:28:39.820
So now I must kill them.

1021
01:28:40.779 --> 01:28:43.321
Again and again.

1022
01:28:43.323 --> 01:28:47.327
In different forms.
like shades. Again.

1023
01:28:48.704 --> 01:28:50.872
And again.
and it never ceases.

1024
01:28:54.500 --> 01:28:56.211
It's a curse. Godwyn.

1025
01:28:58.046 --> 01:28:59.713
And it's one
you bring on yourself.

1026
01:28:59.715 --> 01:29:02.425
even if done through duty.

1027
01:29:03.426 --> 01:29:05.428
It cares not about your duty.

1028
01:29:06.221 --> 01:29:09.224
This world cares
only about blood.

1029
01:29:10.976 --> 01:29:13.186
And blood is all
it will give in return.

1030
01:29:15.897 --> 01:29:18.859
But do you want
to kill a child. Godwyn?

1031
01:29:21.152 --> 01:29:22.777
Do you want to be responsible

1032
01:29:22.779 --> 01:29:25.198
for the killing
of a little girl?

1033
01:29:26.157 --> 01:29:27.200
(SNIFFLES)

1034
01:29:28.619 --> 01:29:29.828
(VOICE BREAKING) No.

1035
01:29:41.673 --> 01:29:43.174
Your father's dead?

1036
01:29:44.760 --> 01:29:45.842
And your uncles?

1037
01:29:45.844 --> 01:29:47.053
(SNIFFLES)

1038
01:29:49.014 --> 01:29:50.766
I am the eldest left.

1039
01:29:52.225 --> 01:29:53.226
(SIGHS)

1040
01:29:55.436 --> 01:29:56.813
Who else yet lives. Godwyn?

1041
01:29:59.357 --> 01:30:00.441
My mother.

1042
01:30:02.235 --> 01:30:03.278
My aunts.

1043
01:30:04.780 --> 01:30:06.404
My sisters.

1044
01:30:06.406 --> 01:30:08.324
You have a home. Godwyn?

1045
01:30:10.661 --> 01:30:12.412
-Yes.
-Go home.

1046
01:30:13.747 --> 01:30:16.374
Tell your family
all blood debts are paid.

1047
01:30:17.083 --> 01:30:18.877
They'll all be paid someday.

1048
01:30:21.087 --> 01:30:22.422
Sleep in your own bed.

1049
01:30:23.715 --> 01:30:25.882
Hold dear the life

1050
01:30:25.884 --> 01:30:28.011
you will yet share
with your kin.

1051
01:30:29.596 --> 01:30:31.306
And if you return here.

1052
01:30:32.432 --> 01:30:34.015
you will have wasted
this chance

1053
01:30:34.017 --> 01:30:35.936
at life that I give you now.

1054
01:30:37.729 --> 01:30:39.604
And I will cut your throat

1055
01:30:39.606 --> 01:30:41.357
and never think of you again.

1056
01:30:48.239 --> 01:30:49.282
Go now.

1057
01:30:51.785 --> 01:30:53.078
And do not look back.

1058
01:31:06.842 --> 01:31:08.552
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

1059
01:31:26.820 --> 01:31:28.989
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

1060
01:31:47.799 --> 01:31:50.091
I thought
you had departed. (SOBS)

1061
01:31:50.093 --> 01:31:52.095
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

1062
01:31:59.811 --> 01:32:01.312
I am Robin the Outlaw.

1063
01:32:05.025 --> 01:32:08.695
You... You need to know
that I'm a monster.

1064
01:32:11.031 --> 01:32:12.490
I'm not one Randolph.

1065
01:32:15.243 --> 01:32:18.496
I am the outlaw. Robin Hood.

1066
01:32:20.290 --> 01:32:22.458
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1067
01:32:28.840 --> 01:32:30.801
(SOBBING BREATHS)

1068
01:32:33.094 --> 01:32:35.263
(MUMBLES) I'm sorry...

1069
01:32:39.225 --> 01:32:41.394
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1070
01:32:50.111 --> 01:32:51.362
(GRUNTS)

1071
01:33:02.040 --> 01:33:03.414
(FIRE CRACKLES)

1072
01:33:03.416 --> 01:33:05.669
(DRAMATIC MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

1073
01:33:18.306 --> 01:33:19.516
(WILD BOAR GRUNTS)

1074
01:33:21.184 --> 01:33:23.353
(BOWSTRING STRETCHING)

1075
01:33:37.784 --> 01:33:38.658
(ARROW THUDS)

1076
01:33:38.660 --> 01:33:40.829
(WILD BOAR'S BODY DRAGGING)

1077
01:33:57.971 --> 01:33:58.930
(GROANS)

1078
01:34:04.227 --> 01:34:06.396
(DRAMATIC MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

1079
01:34:12.903 --> 01:34:13.945
(MUSIC FADES)

1080
01:34:15.614 --> 01:34:17.616
(PANTING)

1081
01:34:35.634 --> 01:34:37.093
Tell me I should leave.

1082
01:34:39.930 --> 01:34:40.972
I will go now.

1083
01:34:49.147 --> 01:34:50.440
Get in the bed.

1084
01:35:10.418 --> 01:35:12.128
-Brigid...
-Lie down.

1085
01:35:39.030 --> 01:35:39.990
(BOWL CLATTERS)

1086
01:35:52.544 --> 01:35:54.630
(ROBIN SIGHS)

1087
01:35:57.758 --> 01:35:59.593
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

1088
01:36:07.350 --> 01:36:09.520
(BLOOD CONTINUES DRIPPING)

1089
01:36:22.824 --> 01:36:24.993
(TRAGIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1090
01:36:36.755 --> 01:36:38.924
(BREATHING SLOWS)

1091
01:37:10.622 --> 01:37:11.790
(SIGHS SOFTLY)

1092
01:37:15.335 --> 01:37:16.670
(SIGHS)

1093
01:37:19.840 --> 01:37:22.050
(TRAGIC MUSIC
CONTINUES PLAYING)

1094
01:37:26.888 --> 01:37:28.098
(DOOR CLOSES)

1095
01:37:41.570 --> 01:37:43.069
(LAUGHS)

1096
01:37:43.071 --> 01:37:45.240
(DISTURBING MUSIC PLAYING)

1097
01:37:47.576 --> 01:37:49.745
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

1098
01:38:38.043 --> 01:38:40.295
You burned my husband alive.

1099
01:38:45.801 --> 01:38:47.300
I dream that
he was already dead.

1100
01:38:47.302 --> 01:38:50.055
but why else did you bar
the door? (SOBS)

1101
01:38:54.643 --> 01:38:56.017
It felt like a lifetime

1102
01:38:56.019 --> 01:38:58.564
searching the ashes
of our home.

1103
01:39:01.900 --> 01:39:03.610
And he looked so small.

1104
01:39:05.612 --> 01:39:09.449
Curled up in the corner
with so much of him gone.

1105
01:39:14.120 --> 01:39:15.620
But as much as I dream.

1106
01:39:15.622 --> 01:39:17.123
I know he was alive.

1107
01:39:21.837 --> 01:39:23.670
Because. until the very end.

1108
01:39:23.672 --> 01:39:25.129
he had wrapped himself

1109
01:39:25.131 --> 01:39:27.175
around our children.

1110
01:39:34.558 --> 01:39:36.267
(EXHALES)

1111
01:39:37.060 --> 01:39:39.270
(TRAGIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1112
01:40:00.584 --> 01:40:02.544
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1113
01:40:05.130 --> 01:40:06.590
(DOOR CLOSES)

1114
01:40:08.592 --> 01:40:10.010
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1115
01:40:10.844 --> 01:40:12.303
(DOOR RATTLES)

1116
01:40:14.765 --> 01:40:16.683
-LITTLE MARGARET: Randolph...
-(GASPS SOFTLY)

1117
01:40:18.769 --> 01:40:20.020
...it's me.

1118
01:40:21.980 --> 01:40:24.063
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1119
01:40:24.065 --> 01:40:26.525
(FOOTSTEPS RECEDING)

1120
01:40:26.527 --> 01:40:28.570
(SOBBING SOFTLY)

1121
01:40:38.246 --> 01:40:40.456
(SISTER BRIGID SOBBING)

1122
01:41:02.604 --> 01:41:04.731
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

1123
01:41:14.199 --> 01:41:16.367
ROBIN: People speak
of Robin Hood.

1124
01:41:18.203 --> 01:41:19.370
(ROBIN SIGHS)

1125
01:41:21.331 --> 01:41:22.916
Tell his stories.

1126
01:41:29.297 --> 01:41:30.841
They're all lies.

1127
01:41:34.845 --> 01:41:37.556
Lies that I told long ago.

1128
01:41:39.224 --> 01:41:40.809
So that fools would...

1129
01:41:42.352 --> 01:41:44.437
follow me into the dark.

1130
01:41:46.189 --> 01:41:48.399
(BREATHING WEAKLY)

1131
01:41:53.989 --> 01:41:56.742
EDWARD: Robin. (ECHOING)

1132
01:42:01.580 --> 01:42:03.498
What have they done to you?

1133
01:42:09.420 --> 01:42:11.297
EDWARD: Don't be afraid.

1134
01:42:13.299 --> 01:42:15.969
I will rescue you
from this place.

1135
01:42:18.054 --> 01:42:20.348
I'll rescue Little Margaret.

1136
01:42:21.892 --> 01:42:25.061
And we're gonna start
a new life together.

1137
01:42:25.771 --> 01:42:26.813
Edward...

1138
01:42:31.192 --> 01:42:33.403
tell me about your wife.

1139
01:42:37.282 --> 01:42:39.492
(ROBIN BREATHING WEAKLY)

1140
01:42:43.163 --> 01:42:44.372
My wife.

1141
01:42:47.167 --> 01:42:48.376
ROBIN: Margaret.

1142
01:42:52.505 --> 01:42:53.715
(SOFTLY) Margaret.

1143
01:42:56.092 --> 01:42:58.011
My wife. Margaret.

1144
01:43:00.305 --> 01:43:01.890
Paint a portrait.

1145
01:43:04.475 --> 01:43:05.852
EDWARD: Paint a portrait?

1146
01:43:10.273 --> 01:43:11.692
She has hair...

1147
01:43:13.944 --> 01:43:15.070
red like...

1148
01:43:16.863 --> 01:43:18.740
the setting sun.

1149
01:43:21.577 --> 01:43:24.830
Like the setting summer sun.

1150
01:43:32.128 --> 01:43:33.129
Red like...

1151
01:43:34.005 --> 01:43:36.174
the setting summer...

1152
01:43:37.258 --> 01:43:38.552
sun.

1153
01:43:41.096 --> 01:43:42.303
(GASPS)

1154
01:43:42.305 --> 01:43:44.140
(INDISTINCT VOICES WHISPERING)

1155
01:43:56.778 --> 01:43:57.779
Robin...

1156
01:44:03.869 --> 01:44:06.162
Have you found
your right death?

1157
01:44:11.627 --> 01:44:13.712
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

1158
01:44:39.530 --> 01:44:41.698
(LIMPING FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

1159
01:44:51.875 --> 01:44:52.834
(GRUNTS)

1160
01:44:53.627 --> 01:44:55.837
(PANTING)

1161
01:45:07.015 --> 01:45:09.059
(SOFTLY)
I'm ready to finish it.

1162
01:45:16.232 --> 01:45:17.984
I owe this life to you.

1163
01:45:25.784 --> 01:45:27.285
(WHISPERING) It is monstrous.

1164
01:45:31.790 --> 01:45:33.792
But I owe this life to you.

1165
01:45:34.500 --> 01:45:36.086
You owe me nothing.

1166
01:45:41.508 --> 01:45:43.802
I have never taken
a life before.

1167
01:45:45.303 --> 01:45:46.304
Ah.

1168
01:45:48.056 --> 01:45:50.726
It can be
as if pruning a flower.

1169
01:45:52.644 --> 01:45:54.393
Well. it should not be.

1170
01:45:54.395 --> 01:45:56.732
Aye. it should not.

1171
01:45:58.358 --> 01:45:59.484
But it can.

1172
01:46:05.281 --> 01:46:07.909
I help those
who come to this island.

1173
01:46:10.704 --> 01:46:11.955
I heal them.

1174
01:46:16.084 --> 01:46:17.127
Please.

1175
01:46:22.633 --> 01:46:24.050
Heal me.

1176
01:46:28.805 --> 01:46:31.016
(SERENE MUSIC PLAYING)

1177
01:47:19.815 --> 01:47:21.357
Little Margaret...

1178
01:47:27.155 --> 01:47:29.449
your father's name were John.

1179
01:47:38.917 --> 01:47:41.044
I knew him for many years.

1180
01:47:42.212 --> 01:47:44.380
Before he were your papa.

1181
01:47:46.925 --> 01:47:48.176
(GRUNTS WEAKLY)

1182
01:47:50.386 --> 01:47:51.513
I met him...

1183
01:47:53.139 --> 01:47:55.225
crossing a bridge one day...

1184
01:47:56.810 --> 01:47:59.062
over a rushing river.

1185
01:48:01.607 --> 01:48:03.066
He was stubborn.

1186
01:48:06.111 --> 01:48:08.528
He would not yield.

1187
01:48:08.530 --> 01:48:11.658
Oh. not to any man.

1188
01:48:13.159 --> 01:48:14.578
Not even to me.

1189
01:48:17.998 --> 01:48:19.499
So we wrestled.

1190
01:48:20.458 --> 01:48:21.627
On that bridge.

1191
01:48:23.837 --> 01:48:27.048
Striking. Back and forth.

1192
01:48:29.092 --> 01:48:31.553
I whacked him
on the side of the head.

1193
01:48:34.097 --> 01:48:36.266
He struck me in the stomach.

1194
01:48:37.768 --> 01:48:40.061
And I wobbled on that bridge.

1195
01:48:41.813 --> 01:48:43.064
Splash!

1196
01:48:44.315 --> 01:48:46.527
-He knocked me on me bum.
-(CHUCKLES)

1197
01:48:50.405 --> 01:48:52.533
Once I dragged myself out.

1198
01:48:53.659 --> 01:48:55.243
drenched to the bone.

1199
01:48:57.037 --> 01:48:58.246
we embraced.

1200
01:49:01.917 --> 01:49:03.501
We called your papa...

1201
01:49:04.545 --> 01:49:05.629
Little John.

1202
01:49:07.213 --> 01:49:09.382
And we lived for many years...

1203
01:49:12.761 --> 01:49:16.222
as outlaws in the greenwood.

1204
01:49:19.184 --> 01:49:20.811
Oh. we had feasts.

1205
01:49:22.395 --> 01:49:23.396
We...

1206
01:49:23.980 --> 01:49:25.398
We gave silver...

1207
01:49:26.567 --> 01:49:27.609
to the meek.

1208
01:49:32.197 --> 01:49:33.740
(SOFTLY) No...

1209
01:49:44.918 --> 01:49:47.212
But we stole that silver.

1210
01:49:52.968 --> 01:49:54.219
We stole it...

1211
01:49:55.887 --> 01:49:59.182
from. from bad people.

1212
01:50:03.979 --> 01:50:05.230
(SOFTLY) You understand?

1213
01:50:07.816 --> 01:50:08.859
Bad people.

1214
01:50:18.744 --> 01:50:20.746
(BREATHING WEAKLY)

1215
01:50:24.290 --> 01:50:25.542
Your papa...

1216
01:50:27.043 --> 01:50:28.795
would want me to tell you...

1217
01:50:34.801 --> 01:50:37.554
because he loved you
so dearly.

1218
01:50:41.307 --> 01:50:43.769
You must never tell a soul.

1219
01:50:45.311 --> 01:50:47.689
Not even the children
you play with.

1220
01:50:49.357 --> 01:50:52.986
You must never tell them
your papa's name.

1221
01:50:57.240 --> 01:50:59.325
There are
bad people out there.

1222
01:51:02.162 --> 01:51:05.832
And they are angry
with your papa.

1223
01:51:07.292 --> 01:51:08.459
(ROBIN SIGHS)

1224
01:51:10.211 --> 01:51:12.295
(SOFTLY)
And so they're angry with you.

1225
01:51:12.297 --> 01:51:13.632
(SOBBING QUIETLY)

1226
01:51:17.343 --> 01:51:19.721
And can we keep that secret?

1227
01:51:21.848 --> 01:51:24.643
I can keep that secret.
Little Margaret.

1228
01:51:27.145 --> 01:51:28.396
Can you?

1229
01:51:32.984 --> 01:51:34.528
ROBIN: Good.

1230
01:51:36.487 --> 01:51:37.989
Now come beside me.

1231
01:51:41.242 --> 01:51:42.452
(SNIFFLES)

1232
01:51:48.208 --> 01:51:49.459
Take this.

1233
01:51:51.377 --> 01:51:52.713
Why were he "Little"?

1234
01:51:53.964 --> 01:51:54.965
What?

1235
01:51:56.132 --> 01:51:58.299
Why were my papa
called "Little"?

1236
01:51:58.301 --> 01:52:00.512
(ROBIN BREATHING SHALLOW)

1237
01:52:03.890 --> 01:52:06.476
Because he were little
when I found him.

1238
01:52:08.269 --> 01:52:09.393
Like you.

1239
01:52:09.395 --> 01:52:11.565
(TENDER MUSIC PLAYING)

1240
01:52:17.529 --> 01:52:18.780
String it.

1241
01:52:41.970 --> 01:52:45.140
Bend it with your leg
as you saw me do.

1242
01:52:53.649 --> 01:52:54.983
(BOW CREAKS)

1243
01:53:02.032 --> 01:53:03.033
(SOFTLY) Good.

1244
01:53:04.576 --> 01:53:08.329
Now. go to the window.

1245
01:53:16.797 --> 01:53:18.674
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1246
01:53:25.514 --> 01:53:27.683
(TENDER MUSIC CONTINUES)

1247
01:53:29.142 --> 01:53:30.185
Now.

1248
01:53:32.270 --> 01:53:33.313
nock an arrow.

1249
01:53:42.197 --> 01:53:43.406
Find a point

1250
01:53:44.616 --> 01:53:46.993
where the waters meet the sky.

1251
01:53:52.040 --> 01:53:54.292
Pull that arrow to your mouth.

1252
01:53:58.421 --> 01:53:59.715
And hold.

1253
01:54:01.550 --> 01:54:03.677
I will tell you when to loose.

1254
01:54:06.680 --> 01:54:08.098
And when I do...

1255
01:54:09.265 --> 01:54:10.767
you're not letting go.

1256
01:54:13.645 --> 01:54:15.981
You're simply
not holding on anymore.

1257
01:54:21.027 --> 01:54:22.028
Now.

1258
01:54:23.572 --> 01:54:25.073
Watch that target.

1259
01:54:28.201 --> 01:54:30.746
Your body
will always be moving.

1260
01:54:33.790 --> 01:54:38.294
Feel when that arrow
will fly true.

1261
01:54:41.632 --> 01:54:43.842
You're gonna find a dance.

1262
01:54:46.011 --> 01:54:48.514
Hold until I tell you
to loose.

1263
01:54:52.267 --> 01:54:53.894
You are strong.

1264
01:54:54.853 --> 01:54:56.437
Feel...

1265
01:54:58.231 --> 01:54:59.482
that sway.

1266
01:55:03.194 --> 01:55:04.279
that dance.

1267
01:55:10.243 --> 01:55:11.492
(MUSIC FADES)

1268
01:55:11.494 --> 01:55:12.994
Now loose.

1269
01:55:12.996 --> 01:55:16.207
-(ARROW FIRES)
-(WAVES CRASHING)

1270
01:55:26.426 --> 01:55:28.428
(TENDER MUSIC RESUMES)

1271
01:57:04.315 --> 01:57:06.484
(SOLEMN MUSIC PLAYING)

1272
02:01:54.230 --> 02:01:55.231
(MUSIC FADES)

1272
02:01:56.305 --> 02:02:56.333
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
